Predicting Alpha Signal using Microblogging Data¶

Alpha Signal is used to make purchase decision on stocks. This is currently predicted using seven stock factors. To predict Alpha more accurately, data is gathered from a microblogging site: 'Stocktwits'. Brokers and stockers tweet about the company in this microblogging site and tag the company with 'tickers', that start with a dollar sign¶
Our goal is to do find out the sentiment of these tweets and generate a sentiment score. This sentiment score will be used as an additional factor in prediction of Alpha with the previous 7 factors. The assumption being that the inclusion of sentiment score will give a better understanding of the company at the ground level and will help the investors to decide whether to invest in that particular stock or not.¶

What is Alpha Signal?¶

Alpha is a metric used to gauge the outperformance of a trading portfolio over a normalised portfolio. It is one of modern portfolio theory’s statistical measures used to quantify the returns made from an investment against a benchmark. In general, a better value of alpha means the better an investment performed against market indices.¶
A single integer value represents the metric. A positive alpha value indicates that the fund performed better than benchmarks, while a negative value denotes the opposite. So an alpha of 1 tells you that investment is doing 1% better than the benchmark value. An alpha of -2 on the other hands shows you’ve underperformed against the benchmark by 2%.¶

How will Sentiment Analysis play a role in predecting Alpha Signal¶

Given its importance, investment managers are constantly on the lookout for means to generate alpha for the funds they handle. Hence they are always on the lookout for any data that would influence or better that alpha value. A major factor would be sentiment data to indicate if a particular stock, currency, or market is going to move in a certain direction. Having alpha signals and sentiment data can facilitate a massive and seemingly “unfair” advantage over their competitors.¶

def readJsonFromFile(pathOfFile):
    with open (pathOfFile) as f:

    return json_data

"""
This function removes any URL present 
"""

def remove_urls(text):
    url_pattern = re.compile(r'https?://\S+|www\.\S+')
    return url_pattern.sub(r' ', text)

    return html_pattern.sub(r' ', text)

"""
This function coverts Emoticons to Text
"""

def convert_emoticons(text):
    for emot in EMOTICONS:
        text = re.sub(u'('+emot+')', "_".join(EMOTICONS[emot].replace(","," ").split()), text)
    return text

PUNCT_TO_REMOVE = string.punctuation
def remove_punctuation(text):
    return text.translate(str.maketrans(PUNCT_TO_REMOVE, ' ' * len(string.punctuation))).replace(' '*4, ' ').replace(' '*3, ' ').replace(' '*2, ' ').strip()

"""
Conversion of string into List
"""

chat_words_map_dict = {}
chat_words_list = []
for line in chat_words_str.split("\n"):
    if line != "":
        cw = line.split("=")[0]
        cw_expanded = line.split("=")[1]
        chat_words_list.append(cw)
        chat_words_map_dict[cw] = cw_expanded
chat_words_list = set(chat_words_list)

"""
Custom function to convert chat words to Text
"""

def chat_words_conversion(text):
    new_text = []
    for w in text.split():
        if w.upper() in chat_words_list:
            new_text.append(chat_words_map_dict[w.upper()])
        else:
            new_text.append(w)
    return " ".join(new_text).lower()

def drawWordCloud(score=0,colName='text_clean'):
      token_text=word_tokenize(collateScoreText(colName,score))

def changeDateFormat(date):
    dt = datetime.strptime(str(date),'%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')

def selectModel(train_X,train_y, model):

def plotLearningCurve(train_sizes,model,scoring,train_X,train_y):
    if model == 'MultinomialNB':
        estimator = MultinomialNB()
    elif model == 'ComplementNB':
        estimator = ComplementNB()
    elif model == 'MLP':
        estimator = MLPClassifier()
    elif model == 'DecisionTreeClassifier':
        estimator = DecisionTreeClassifier()
    elif model == 'XGBClassifier':
        estimator = XGBClassifier()
        
    train_sizes, train_scores, validation_scores = learning_curve(
    estimator = estimator,
    X = train_X,
    y = train_y, train_sizes = train_sizes, cv = 5,
    scoring = scoring)
    
    print('Training scores:\n\n', train_scores)
    print('\n', '-' * 70) # separator to make the output easy to read
    print('\nValidation scores:\n\n', validation_scores)
    
    train_scores_mean = train_scores.mean(axis = 1)
    validation_scores_mean = validation_scores.mean(axis = 1)
    
    print('Mean training scores\n\n', pd.Series(train_scores_mean, index = train_sizes))
    print('\n', '-' * 20) # separator
    print('\nMean validation scores\n\n',pd.Series(validation_scores_mean, index = train_sizes))
    
    plt.style.use('seaborn')
    plt.plot(train_sizes, train_scores_mean, label = 'Training Macro F1 score ')
    plt.plot(train_sizes, validation_scores_mean, label = 'Validation Macro F1 score')
    plt.ylabel('Macro F1 Score', fontsize = 14)
    plt.xlabel('Training set size', fontsize = 14)
    plt.title('Learning curves for a {} model'.format(model), fontsize = 18, y = 1.03)
    plt.legend()
    plt.ylim(0,1)

def tickerInMonth(month):
